flowRoot.flowPara: A Distributed Evolutionary Approach to Image Approximation and Compression

We decided to usde genetic algorithms to approximate the target image. Genetic algorithms mimic the biological processes of natural selection, recombination, and mutation to find the optimal solution to a problem. We chose a genetic approach in order approximate the image in a way that's much faster than brute force.

We distributed our algorithm onto a parallel computing cluster in which each node operates its own genetic "island". The best results from each node are periodically shared with the other nodes in order to prevent extreme divergence.
Our algorithm approximates a raster image by trying to find the optimal arrangement of opaque polygons that approximate that raster image. Each triangle is given a color and opacity.

It varies depending on the exact parameters, but our results typically take about one fifth the space of an uncompressed image, however this is still larger (and less accurate) than many mainstream image formats like jpeg

The genetic algorithm converges very quickly at the beginning but then gets stuck in local optima where any changes necessary to move forward are either highly improbable or impossible. We have begun adding variations that do not mimic nature in order to mitigate this
